Welcome to the=C2=A0873=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined u=
s since last Monday =E2=80=94 I need to take breaks more often! If you have=
n=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0155,416 smart, curious folks by subscribi=
ng here:=20
=F0=9F=8E=A7=C2=A0 For the audio version, listen on Spotify [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/664b9af5-2cdb-46aa-9bf2-6343cae921d0?r=3D9p0gt ] or=C2=A0A=
pple Podcasts [ https://substack.com/redirect/0376bd8f-5a40-42bc-96f4-dca88=
ac78d54?r=3D9p0gt ]
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Monday! Big week here at Not Boring HQ: Friday was Puja and my 5th an=
niversary (Happy Anniversary Puj!), tomorrow is Dev=E2=80=99s 2nd birthday,=
 and Thursday is Maya=E2=80=99s 2-month birthday.=C2=A0
Last year, when Dev turned 1, I wrote Dad Life [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/f472625b-1103-4c0b-b318-442a63ac4fc1?r=3D9p0gt ], a piece about working=
 and raising a kid at the same time. I wasn=E2=80=99t planning on writing a=
 similar piece for his birthday this year, but I=E2=80=99ve been thinking a=
 lot about a related question and the timing worked perfectly.=C2=A0
The question is: how the hell are you supposed to educate a kid today?=C2=
=A0
Dev and Maya get a blank educational slate to start with. Puja and I are re=
sponsible for figuring out how to give them the best education possible, on=
e that helps them love learning, have fun, and get prepared for life beyond=
 school. I don=E2=80=99t think the answer is as simple as =E2=80=9CGet them=
 into the best schools possible.=E2=80=9D I think it=E2=80=99s a lot more c=
omplicated than that, and will only get more complicated as things move fas=
ter.=C2=A0
This isn=E2=80=99t meant to be a complete survey and analysis of the modern=
 educational system, it=E2=80=99s more of an exploration of how I=E2=80=99m=
 thinking about it personally in the very specific context of Dev and Maya=
=E2=80=99s education. What=E2=80=99s the best way to prepare my two kids?=
=C2=A0
And I don=E2=80=99t have the answers =E2=80=93 there=E2=80=99s probably no =
=E2=80=9Cright=E2=80=9D answer. Instead, this is meant to start a conversat=
ion, and selfishly, to give me some more direction as I think through it. I=
=E2=80=99d love to hear your thoughts, jump in here:=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
How Do I Teach These Kids?!
Now that we have kids, my most important job is raising them. I want them t=
o be happy and kind and smart and creative and hard-working and a little de=
vilish. I remember walking around holding Dev when he was really little and=
 telling him those things, listing the qualities I wanted to instill in him=
 as if he could absorb the words and make them so. In reality, it=E2=80=99s=
 a lot harder than that.=C2=A0
A timely example. Last night, after we had our family over to celebrate his=
 birthday, I gave him a bath, put him in his pajamas, and started reading h=
im a book, Goodnight, Goodnight Construction Site [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/587a0ef8-165f-4851-b9fe-d708f6707e6e?r=3D9p0gt ] to be exact. As we =
were finishing =E2=80=93 =E2=80=9CGreat work today! Now=E2=80=A6shh=E2=80=
=A6goodnight!=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 my mind was already on getting back to wor=
k and finishing this piece. I was tired, and starting back up after a long =
day was already daunting enough. When he asked, =E2=80=9CCan we read one mo=
re book please?=E2=80=9D I started to shake my head no, tell him it was tim=
e to go to sleep, that dad had to work=E2=80=A6 and then I remembered what =
I was about to go work on: an essay about educating him and his sister. The=
 hypocrisy was too thick. We read another book.=C2=A0
There are a million little trade-offs like that, though rarely quite so on =
the nose. Historically, the way to deal with a big lump of those trade-offs=
 is, eventually, to try to put your kids in the best schools possible and m=
ake sure that they=E2=80=99re doing their homework and getting good grades =
and doing all of the extracurriculars, which serve double duty as resume fi=
llers and extra childcare.=C2=A0
But thanks to the pandemic and our jobs, Puja and I have been lucky enough =
to be home most of the time, getting to spend time with Dev and Maya, getti=
ng to watch them get smarter every day, like little human large language mo=
dels with big emotions. At the same time, the real large language models ha=
ve been getting stronger by the day, surprisingly upending creative work fi=
rst, which has made me reflect on what the world will look like when they=
=E2=80=99re older, and how to prepare them for that world. What will people=
 need to know in a world in which the Enchanted Notebook [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/2cee0fbb-b004-4b22-90e1-9960416bbc3e?r=3D9p0gt ] exists?
While we=E2=80=99ll still put them in school =E2=80=93 Dev started a couple=
 weeks ago, for a few hours three days a week =E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99s become=
 clear that if we want them to grow up to be uniquely them to the fullest o=
f their potential, and stay ahead of seemingly daily advances, we need to d=
o a lot more than that.=C2=A0
The question is, what? And I guess another one is, how? How do we teach the=
se kids?!=C2=A0
There are these charts that pop up every once in a while that show how much=
 graduates of certain majors make or which majors are becoming more popular=
=2E=C2=A0
One that has recently caught peoples=E2=80=99 attention is this chart that =
shows that computer science degrees are on the rise, and humanities degrees=
 are on an equal and opposite decline. This chart has caused either celebra=
tion (=E2=80=9CGood! People are studying things that will help them get job=
s.=E2=80=9D) or anguish (=E2=80=9COh no! The death of humanities will lead =
to a duller, less ethical and moral society.=E2=80=9D).=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t have a strong view. What struck me when I looked at the cha=
rt, and the related hot takes on Twitter, was just how hard it must be for =
educational institutions at all levels to keep up with the increasing rate =
of change in the world.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s an oft-cited fact that the modern education system was created=
 during the Industrial Revolution to prepare children to grow up to work in=
 factories. =E2=80=9CFactory schools,=E2=80=9D as they were called, sprang =
up in Prussia in the 19th Century and quickly spread throughout the industr=
ialized world, to teach kids to be =E2=80=9Cpunctual, docile, and sober [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/aef0cc00-ae0f-4e4a-bd5e-23fcba4385ba?r=3D9p0gt=
 ].=E2=80=9D Moving from the family farm to the corporate factory required =
a different set of skills and behaviors, and schools stepped in to teach th=
em.=C2=A0
That model worked well, and persisted for two centuries, in part, I would g=
uess, because the types of jobs that people were going to get after school,=
 and the skills they would need for those jobs, stayed relatively static. A=
nd a literate, numerate population trained to follow orders generalized wel=
l. The Man in the Gray Flannel Suit [ https://substack.com/redirect/fdf3b1f=
3-4141-4059-8ffb-6d8ce875205e?r=3D9p0gt ] worked in an office instead of a =
factory, and wore nicer clothes, but was still expected to be punctual, doc=
ile, and sober.=C2=A0
While some of the details have changed, the system works largely the same w=
ay today, even among the top students at the best schools.=C2=A0
When I asked people for their favorite essays [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/1f76ab8e-ffe5-432d-a08d-c9c3f82a027b?r=3D9p0gt ], William Deresiewicz=E2=
=80=99s Solitude and Leadership [ https://substack.com/redirect/b81e9f98-cc=
b7-48b7-8f45-7f685fab657d?r=3D9p0gt ] was one of the most frequently-recomm=
ended (I marked it up with notes in Readwise Reader here [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/2f59b15c-2732-42d6-b810-8=
dc135be3545?r=3D9p0gt ]). The essay =
is the transcript of a talk Deresiewicz, a former Yale English professor an=
d author, gave to the incoming plebe class at West Point in 2009.=C2=A0
While at Yale, Deresiewicz spent some time on the admissions committee, whe=
re he experienced this:=C2=A0
Well, it turned out that a student who had six or seven extracurriculars wa=
s already in trouble. Because the students who got in=E2=80=94in addition t=
o perfect grades and top scores=E2=80=94usually had 10 or 12.
So what I saw around me were great kids who had been trained to be world-cl=
ass hoop jumpers. Any goal you set them, they could achieve. Any test you g=
ave them, they could pass with flying colors. They were, as one of them put=
 it herself, =E2=80=9Cexcellent sheep.=E2=80=9D
I definitely want my kids to be able to get into schools like Yale, if they=
 want and if that still matters then, but I definitely don=E2=80=99t want t=
hem to be excellent sheep. Excellent sheep seldom make history.=C2=A0
While I don=E2=80=99t have answers to the very difficult question of how to=
 educate millions of kids, kids of all backgrounds and levels of income and=
 aptitude and parental support, and I don=E2=80=99t envy those who have to =
come up with those answers, it=E2=80=99s become pretty clear to me that opt=
imizing just for my own kids, the factory school model, or the more modern =
excellent sheep model, won=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0
I say that as an excellent sheep myself. I was lucky enough to go to great =
private schools and to Duke. I was a good student. I did a lot of extracurr=
iculars. I remember one weekend in high school when I had a debate tourname=
nt one night, ran in Pennsylvania Cross Country State Championship (and fin=
ished All-State) the next morning, and drove back to my high school to perf=
orm in the school play that same night. In college, I studied econ, because=
 I wanted to go into finance, and then spent four years in a finance job I =
didn=E2=80=99t love doing work I didn=E2=80=99t really care about and that =
I realized I was worse at than a lot of people who were plain smarter and a=
ctually loved the work.=C2=A0
It took me a decade post-college, and unemployment at the start of a global=
 pandemic, to find the thing that I was uniquely good at: writing a newslet=
ter, of all things.
I think that a lot of the things I did, in a roundabout way, contributed to=
 what Not Boring has become. Debate helped me frame an argument, finance he=
lped me use a spreadsheet, running helped me put in countless hours of hard=
 work with almost no benefit to show for it for over a year. In retrospect,=
 I wouldn=E2=80=99t change a thing about my education because I=E2=80=99m r=
eally happy with where it=E2=80=99s all led. Serendipity is part of the pro=
cess, and my parents raised us to be able to follow it. They led by example=
 =E2=80=93 both leaving good, stable jobs to start their own things =E2=80=
=93 and as a result, my sister, brother, and I all started our own things.=
=C2=A0
But I also want our kids to be better off than us, something that only a de=
pressing 32% of Americans expect to be true for their children:
Finances aside, Dev and Maya will set their own definitions of =E2=80=9Cbet=
ter off=E2=80=9D and their own goals in life, but when I think about how I =
want to guide them, the words =E2=80=9CPhilosopher King and Queen=E2=80=9D =
come to mind.=C2=A0
The idea, put forth by Plato in The Republic, is that the ideal polis, the =
kallipolis, or beautiful city, should be ruled by philosophers who love kno=
wledge, who seek truth and ideals instead of power. It=E2=80=99s an idea as=
 beautiful as it is impractical. Plato is essentially calling for benevolen=
t dictatorship and assuming that there exist people who absolute power woul=
dn=E2=80=99t corrupt absolutely. If some people throughout history may have=
 fit the bill, they=E2=80=99re too few and far between for benevolent dicta=
torship to be a realistic form of governance, so we=E2=80=99re left with de=
mocracy, =E2=80=9Cthe worst form of government =E2=80=93 except for all the=
 others that have been tried.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I still think it=E2=80=99s a good north star for raising a kid, particularl=
y when those kids are going to grow up into a world in which they=E2=80=99l=
l have more power at their fingertips than our generation can even imagine.=
 Dev and Maya won=E2=80=99t be Philosopher King and Queen of the United Sta=
tes, but they=E2=80=99ll be Philosopher King and Queen of their own little =
worlds.=C2=A0
They and their fellow Gen Alphas will command personalized AI and govern de=
centralized organizations and access overwhelming amounts of information an=
d bring ideas to life with Enchanted Notebooks [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/2cee0fbb-b004-4b22-90e1-9960416bbc3e?r=3D9p0gt ] and shape biology itse=
lf, and I think that it=E2=80=99s going to be important for them to grow up=
 with a philosopher=E2=80=99s love of truth and wisdom and a benevolent mon=
arch=E2=80=99s sense of fairness and goodness. And above all else, I want t=
hem to have a critical curiosity and pragmatic optimism, a willingness to e=
xplore new things openly and excitedly but with a more incisive and critica=
l eye than I have.=C2=A0
And I think that the Factory School / Excellent Sheep model is increasingly=
 incapable of making that happen.=C2=A0
For one thing, I have no idea what skills are going to be in-demand in twen=
ty years, when Dev would graduate college, or twenty-two, when Maya would. =
There=E2=80=99s no factory job waiting on the other side, the corporate lad=
der gets more slippery every year, and the well-worn banking/consulting/law=
/medicine path seems less certain.=C2=A0
Ok, well duh consulting and banking aren=E2=80=99t the sure-things they onc=
e were. Everyone who makes real money today knows how to code. That=E2=80=
=99s why college students are abandoning the humanities in favor of compute=
r science. Teach a kid to code, feed her for a lifetime. We sent Dev to a s=
chool that will start to teach him the very basics of coding next year, whe=
n he=E2=80=99s three. That=E2=80=99s the obviously right call, right?=C2=A0
Not so fast.=C2=A0
Ok, so then I=E2=80=99ll teach my kids ~*prompt engineering*~. If AI is the=
 future, then we should teach our kids to get really good at getting AI to =
do exactly what they want, like this young genius, Urdagirl69.=C2=A0
This Reddit post [ https://substack.com/redirect/51346938-9481-4db4-b5bc-97=
88c37feb84?r=3D9p0gt ] went viral last week. An enterprising young student =
figured out that she could use GPT-3 to help write her essays (she used it =
as a starting point, and then made the essays her own). Writing good essays=
 became so easy, in fact, that she was able to write her classmates=E2=80=
=99 essays, too, for a $100 profit.=C2=A0
One teacher replied that, =E2=80=9CIf I learned that my students were submi=
tting AI-written papers, I=E2=80=99d quit. Grading something an AI wrote is=
 an incredibly depressing waste of my life.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
While I sympathize with the teacher =E2=80=93 spending your life grading pa=
pers written by AI does seem incredibly depressing =E2=80=93 I want to teac=
h my kids to be more like Urdagirl69. By that, I don=E2=80=99t specifically=
 mean that I want to teach them how to use GPT-3 to write essays and build =
a modern paper-farm lemonade stand, but that I want to teach them to have t=
he curiosity, agency, and initiative to use whatever tools they have at the=
ir disposal to do the best work possible.=C2=A0
Urdagirl69 seems excellent, but not sheep-like. GPT-3 will be ancient, anci=
ent technology by the time Dev and Maya are assigned their first essay, but=
 the erudite impishness required to seek out and deploy whatever the curren=
t most advanced technology is in order to do their work, even if it=E2=80=
=99s kind of against the rules, is something I want to instill in them.=C2=
=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean that there shouldn=E2=80=99t be rules, or that we=
 should teach them to break the rules for rule-breaking=E2=80=99s sake. Set=
ting boundaries seems important, if only so they can find creative ways aro=
und them.=C2=A0
On a recent Lunar Society podcast episode [ https://substack.com/redirect/2=
f02832a-8125-44d1-baf0-7af1dafb3328?r=3D9p0gt ], Dwarkesh Patel asked Tyler=
 Cowen if we should just let high schoolers go wild and educate themselves =
without structure, and Cowen=E2=80=99s response seems instructive for desig=
ning educational systems in a world in which kids can write essays with AI:=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI think they need some structure, but you have to let them rebel a=
gainst it, and do their own thing also.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
To read the rest of the piece, including thoughts from Patrick Collison, Er=
ik Hoel, and Emad Mostaque and the 10 things I=E2=80=99m going to focus on:
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/98d0fa2c-0ae5-4f8f-9d13-09ec8=
4991f08?r=3D9p0gt ] and Puja [ https://substack.com/redirect/fd6edcd7-40ac-=
4c11-82f8-fcc32d2bc226?r=3D9p0gt ] for reading and editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. See you back here Friday for your Weekly Dose=
 of Optimism. Have a great week.=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

